Exploring the BRFSS data

Setup

Load packages

library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)

Load data

load("brfss2013.RData")

Part 1: Data

Our dataset includes a lot of various features related to lifestyle such as health conditions, whether a person is an adult or not, their height/weight, how often do they take different medical tests and more.

The data is collected via both landline telephone and cellular telephone-based surveys from each of the 50 locations and participants are US citizens that are at least 18 years old. In the landline surveys, participants are randomly selected adults in a household. In the cellular telephone version, participants are adults, who are using cellular telephone and reside in a private residence or college housing.

The results are generalizable to the people in the respective states, since random sampling was used, however, we can’t establish any causal relationships since it is an observational study.

In total there are 491775 observations of 330 variables.

Part 2: Research questions

Research quesion 1: There are quite a few books written about ‘rich’ and ‘successful’ people and their lifestyle. But now we have the data and can check it using various statistical tools.

Thus, the first question I’d like to examine is whether people with high level of education(those who graduated from college) and high level of household income(75000$ or more) are also more prone to take care of their physical health and check the ratio of people smoking in that group compared to the whole population.

Research quesion 2: The second question I’d like to look at how # of sleep hours affects concentration or remembering and general health.

My hypothesis is that there should be at least some correlation, although the required number of hours to sleep usually varies from person to person(e.g. older people typically sleep less).

Research quesion 3:

Here I’d like to check the relationship between physical exercises and body mass index. Although we can’t make any causal inferences out of the relationships between these 2 features, even if they exist, it is still an interesting issue to look into.

Part 3: Exploratory data analysis

rich_and_educated = brfss2013 %>% 
  filter(as.integer(income2) == 8, as.integer(educa) == 6)

Now let’s see how many such participans we got, and what’s the ratio of those participants/total participans. Use round() to limit the output to 2 decimal places.

nrow(rich_and_educated)
## [1] 73800
(nrow(rich_and_educated) / nrow(brfss2013)) %>%
  round(digits=2)
## [1] 0.15

We’re finally ready to check for various correlations by plotting the data. Let’s start with a histogram of the number of days our chosen participants don’t feel good about their physical health. For the sake of simplicity, we’ll use hist() function.

hist(rich_and_educated$physhlth, main="Physical health for the 'rich and educated'", xlab="Number of days sick", ylab="Number of people", col="black", xlim=c(0, 30), breaks=15)

Apparently, most of our selected group, around 60 thousand participants have not been experiencing problems with their health when the data was collected. Let’s try the same thing but with the whole dataset.

hist(brfss2013$physhlth, main="Physical health for the whole sample", xlab="Number of days sick", ylab="Number of people", col="black", xlim=c(0, 30), breaks=30)

Well, the trend is still there. Perhaps, the variable representing physical health for the past 30 days is independent of the features we’ve chosen.

This time, let’s look at smoking ratios. Variable `smokday2’ is the one we’ll make use of. Let’s see what it represents.

So 3 options, now let’s check for the distribution on the whole dataset as well as on our rich_and_educated slice. Let’s first make tables using table() function, as it will help us to manipulate the needed data.

If you look carefully, you might already notice some trend, but let’s create pie charts to make things more apparent. Calculate the percentages first using division and sum() function.

Now let’s move on and build the pie charts using pie() function. First, for the sliced data:

cols = c("red", "lightblue", "lightgreen")

pie(rich_and_educated_table, main="Smoking trend among 'rich and educated'", col=cols, labels=pielabels, cex=1.1)
legend("topright", legend_values, fill=cols)

And then for the whole sample:

pielabels<- paste(percent_sample, "%", sep="")
pie(brfss2013_table, main="Smoking trend among the whole sample", col=cols, labels=pielabels, cex=1.1)
legend("topright", legend_values, fill=cols)

There is a clear difference between our chosen group of participants vs. the whole sample. Let’s now move on to question 2 to explore this dataset further.

Research quesion 2:

So let’s have a look at the useful variables we have at our disposal. The most relevant ones seem to be sleptim1, genhlth, physhlth and menthlth. Let’s check the summary for these 4 variables using summary() function.

Before we do that, however, let’s slice our dataset, it’s more convenient to work with the subset, instead of selecting the columns out of the whole dataset every time.

sleep_and_health = brfss2013[c("sleptim1", "genhlth", "physhlth", "menthlth")]
summary(sleep_and_health)

##  NA's   :7387                         NA's   :10957    NA's   :8627

According to the documentation, all the health features are supposed to have values 0-30 which represents the number of days that a person was in that state of health. And sleptim1 is supposed to be 0-24 representing the average number of hours of sleep per day. However, in our dataset we can see that max for sleptim1 is 450, which already doesn’t look right.

Not only that, but we can also notice that physhlth and menthlth has maximum values above 30, which is also a nonsense.

Let’s remove all the invalid data and build a table to see what we get. Create a few helper variables on the way and construct a new slice. Also, lets get rid of rows containing NA values.

brfss2013$sleptim1_clean = apply(brfss2013['sleptim1'], 1, function(x) ifelse (x <= 24, x, NA))
brfss2013$physhlth_clean = apply(brfss2013['physhlth'], 1, function(x) ifelse (x <= 30, x, NA))
brfss2013$menthlth_clean = apply(brfss2013['menthlth'], 1, function(x) ifelse (x <= 30, x, NA))
sleep_and_health = brfss2013[c("sleptim1_clean", "genhlth", "physhlth_clean", "menthlth_clean")] %>% na.omit
summary(sleep_and_health)
##  sleptim1_clean        genhlth       physhlth_clean   menthlth_clean

##  Max.   :24.000                      Max.   :30.000   Max.   :30.000

Let’s try constructing a scatterplot.

ggplot(sleep_and_health, aes(x = sleep_and_health$genhlth, y = sleep_and_health$sleptim1_clean)) + geom_point()

Ok, this does not really help much. Let’s separate our data by the hours of sleep, take 6-9 hours, less than that and more than that.

sleep6_9 = sleep_and_health %>% filter(sleptim1_clean >= 6 & sleptim1_clean <= 9)
plot(sleep6_9$genhlth,
        main="General health distribution for people with 6-9 hrs of sleep",
        xlab="HEALTH LEVEL", ylab="NUMBER OF PEOPLE")

sleep10_or_more = sleep_and_health %>% filter(sleptim1_clean >= 10)

sleep5_or_less = sleep_and_health %>% filter(sleptim1_clean <= 5)
plot(main="General health distribution for people with 5 or less hrs of sleep", sleep5_or_less$genhlth, xlab="HEALTH LEVEL", ylab="NUMBER OF PEOPLE")

Comparing these 3 plots, we can see that the distribution is leaning towards left when the sleep hours are somewhat adequate(6-9). But the correlation is not that dramatic.

Research quesion 3:

As usual, we start with identifying useful variables. The obvious ones are htm4 which is ‘Computed Height In Meters’ and wtkg3 which is ‘Computed Weight In Kilograms’ according to the documentation. To make things simpler, we could use BMI(body mass index) instead. Let’s see if we already have such a variable at our disposal.

It turns out there is a variable called X_bmi5cat which is exactly what we need. Let’s have a look.

brfss2013$X_bmi5cat %>% summary
##   Underweight Normal weight    Overweight         Obese          NA's 
##          8267        154898        167084        134799         26727

Now let’s see which useful variables are present to figure out the information about physical exercises.

Again, let’s use a pre-comupted variable called X_totinda which gives this information to us in a yes/no format.

brfss2013$X_totinda %>% summary
##                Had physical activity or exercise 
##                                           332461 
## No physical activity or exercise in last 30 days 
##                                           125280 
##                                             NA's 
##                                            34034

Finally, let’s do some visualizations. We’ll create 2 auxilliary datasets: one with Underweight + Normal Weight participants, and the other with Overweight and Obese for easier analysis.

underweight_normal = brfss2013 %>% filter(X_bmi5cat == 'Underweight' | X_bmi5cat == 'Normal weight')
overweight_obese = brfss2013 %>% filter(X_bmi5cat == 'Overweight' | X_bmi5cat == 'Obese')

And now let’s see a percentage or a probability of each of the events for these 2 groups. Starting with underweight and normal weight group.

stats_underweight_normal = underweight_normal$X_totinda %>% summary

What’s the probability of a person exercising out of everyone conforming to this group? Let’s take the total where we will exclude the NAs. There is probably a better way to do it though.

total_underweight_normal = (stats_underweight_normal[1] + stats_underweight_normal[2])
(stats_underweight_normal[1] / total_underweight_normal) %>% round(digits=2)
## Had physical activity or exercise 
##                              0.78

What’s the probability of a person not exercising out of everyone conforming to this group?

(stats_underweight_normal[2] / total_underweight_normal) %>% round(digits=2)
## No physical activity or exercise in last 30 days 
##                                             0.22

And as expected, we get the complement, 1 - 0.78.

Now let’s move on to the overweight and obese group.

stats_overweight_obese = overweight_obese$X_totinda %>% summary

What’s the probability of a person exercising out of everyone conforming to this group?

total_overweight_obese = (stats_overweight_obese[1] + stats_overweight_obese[2])
(stats_overweight_obese[1] / total_overweight_obese) %>% round(digits=2)
## Had physical activity or exercise 
##                               0.7

What’s the probability of a person not exercising out of everyone conforming to this group?

(stats_overweight_obese[2] / total_overweight_obese) %>% round(digits=2)
## No physical activity or exercise in last 30 days 
##                                              0.3

Slightly different, but not by much. Could be due to random noise in data. No apparent correlation found.
